\begin{abstract}
We introduce an extension of the incompressible Euler equations to General Relativity and show that the equations proposed correctly reduce to the incompressible Euler equations in the Newtonian limit as $c\rightarrow \infty$. For the case of constant energy density, we show that the ``rescaled'' pressure satisfies an elliptic equation on each of the hypersurfaces orthogonal to the fluid four-velocity. We expect that this elliptic equation generally induces infinite speed of propagation into the system.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle




\section{Introduction}

Non-relativistic incompressible fluids are studied most actively and are fundamental for modeling many phenomena in nature, ranging from meteorology to condensed matter physics. In Relativity, compressible fluids are investigated to great extend and serve for instance as the basic matter models for cosmology. However, incompressible fluids have rarely been addressed in Relativity, even though Schwarzschild addressed an incompressible fluid already in 1916 \cite{Schwarzschild}. One reason for the absence of papers on incompressible relativistic fluids could be that incompressibility is generally associated with infinite wave speeds, which violate the axioms of Relativity. Nevertheless, a general notion of incompressibility based on the requirement that waves travel at the speed of light has been introduced by Lichnerowicz \cite{Lichnerowicz}, (see also \cite{Disconzi} for local existence). However, as it seems, this condition does not capture the rigid motion of non-relativistic incompressible fluids. 

The objective of this note is to introduce a general notion of incompressible fluids in General Relativity (GR) which captures spatial rigidity and to shed light on the problem of infinite speed of propagation more systematically. 

The starting point of this note is the observation that requiring the particle number density to be constant along the fluid flow gives a physically convincing condition for capturing incompressibility in Relativity, different from \cite{Lichnerowicz}. Note, characterizing incompressibility by requiring the fluid velocity to have zero divergence or the mass density to be constant along the fluid flow, as it is done for non-relativistic fluids, seems problematic at first. Namely, the fluid four-velocity having zero divergence does not seem to adequately capture the \emph{spatial} property of balanced extensions and contractions. Similarly, requiring mass density to be constant along the fluid flow suffers from the fact that mass and energy are equivalent in Relativity, and it is not clear if the condition of mass-energy density being constant along flow lines captures incompressibility correctly. Nevertheless, we show in Section \ref{Sec_proposal} that requiring the particle number density to be constant along the fluid flow indeed implies the previous two (naive) conditions, which then leads to our proposal of the incompressible Relativistic Euler equations. In Section \ref{Sec_Newtonian_limit} we compute the Newtonian limit of the equations proposed and verify that they reduce to the non-relativistic incompressible Euler equations. In Section \ref{Sec_instantaneity} we show that a rescaled version of the pressure satisfies an elliptic equation on each hypersurface orthogonal to the fluid four-velocity, and we expect this equation to induce infinite speed of propagation into the equations.







