\section{The Newtonian Limit} \label{Sec_Newtonian_limit}

In this section we show formally that the relativistic system \eqref{incomp_rel_Euler} converges to the non-relativistic incompressible Euler equations as $c\rightarrow \infty$. The non-relativistic incompressible Euler equations are given by    
\begin{eqnarray}
\nabla \cdot {v} &=& 0, \label{incomp_Euler_classical_1} \\
\rho_t + v\cdot \nabla \rho &=& 0, \label{incomp_Euler_classical_2} \\
 \rho\left( v_t + v\cdot\nabla v\right) + \nabla p &=& 0, \label{incomp_Euler_classical_3}
\end{eqnarray}
where $v\in {\mathbb{R}}^3$ is the fluid three-velocity, $\rho$ denotes its mass-density, $\nabla$ is the gradient on ${\mathbb{R}}^3$ and $\nabla \cdot {v}$ is the divergence of $v$ in ${\mathbb{R}}^3$, c.f.\cite{MajdaBertozzi}. The above equations are a system of five equations in the unknowns $v$, $\rho$ and $p$. 

The incompressible relativistic Euler equations, \eqref{incomp_rel_Euler}, are equivalent to \eqref{zero_4-div} - \eqref{rel_balance_momentum}, that is, to the system
